{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621154"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:50:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:50:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16671"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16671"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66253"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16671"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51702"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1498"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66253"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of severe, burning left-sided facial pain followed by the development of a vesicular rash. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The rash is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves has been affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["III","IV","V","VI","VII"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with herpes zoster (shingles) affecting the maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve. There is a cluster of vesicles with some crusting and surrounding erythema in the distribution of the left maxillary region. The rash does not cross the midline and there is no involvement of the eye or forehead. The characteristic presentation includes prodromal pain followed by a unilateral vesicular rash in a dermatomal distribution. The virus remains dormant in sensory nerve ganglia following primary varicella (chickenpox) infection and can reactivate years later, typically in the setting of decreased cell-mediated immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EV\u003C/strong\u003E (trigeminal nerve) provides sensory innervation to the face in three divisions: ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2), and mandibular (V3). The distribution of the rash in this case clearly follows the maxillary (V2) dermatome, confirming trigeminal nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIII\u003C/strong\u003E (oculomotor nerve) is responsible for most extraocular eye movements and pupillary constriction. It does not have a cutaneous sensory distribution and cannot be affected by herpes zoster in this way.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV\u003C/strong\u003E (trochlear nerve) innervates the superior oblique muscle of the eye. Like the oculomotor nerve, it is purely motor and has no sensory distribution that could manifest with this rash pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVI\u003C/strong\u003E (abducens nerve) controls lateral rectus muscle function. It is also a pure motor nerve without cutaneous sensory distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVII\u003C/strong\u003E (facial nerve) provides motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and taste to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue. While it can be affected by herpes zoster (Ramsay Hunt syndrome), this typically presents with ear pain, vesicles in the external auditory canal, and facial paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herpes zoster commonly presents with prodromal pain followed by a vesicular rash in a dermatomal distribution.","The trigeminal nerve (V) has three branches: ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2), and mandibular (V3).","Involvement of the ophthalmic branch of the trigeminal nerve requires urgent ophthalmology review due to risk of sight-threatening complications."],"references":["Patil A, Goldust M, Wollina U. Herpes zoster: A Review of Clinical Manifestations and Management. Viruses 2022; 14:192"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51702"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16671"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21265"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21265"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rG0Z4J7pX4WparloQmpBPbaTRlxQdN.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rG0Z4J7pX4WparloQmpBPbaTRlxQdN.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":316,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51702"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T15:53:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T15:53:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9362"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHea